reviews.review_text: Su90 Tour N5 (Dark Star) The goods!  Easily my favorite, up to this point, of the tour. Rated seventh in DeadBase for 1990's "favorite tapes." The Dark Star is a must-listen. 19 shows after 3/29, it's the only one of the summer and Brent's final version; the next one wouldn't come for another 18 shows, until 9/20 at MSG.

RFK 1990 I was there. Intense experience. In hindsight they should have let the video tapes roll during the first set rain storm instead of covering them with tarp. People would’ve been entertained and amazed. 
High* Points: The best “Feel like a Stranger” IMO. Just listen to Jerry’s guitar run during the solo, it’s sick! Unfortunately, one of his cables came lose at the very end and it wasn’t until midway through his solo on Bertha that Steve Parish, at least I think it was him, jiggled the cable and pesto!  like a bolt of lightning it kicked back on making the last part of the solo soar, and if you listen you can hear the crowd roar.  Back to “Stranger”, Jerry was so dialed in and feeling it that he even did a leg kick at the end of it. Though not quite a ‘70’s jump suit Elvis leg kick, a leg kick none the less. On this  day, Jerry was in good health and absolutely  feeling it. Next High Point: “Bertha”. So even with Jerry’s guitar barely audible through his monitor speaker for at least 1/2 the song, it’s still one of the most powerful versions, hands down. Phil’s thick bass and Brent’s Hammond B3 carry the weight until Jerry’s volume is restored. Both the “Ran into a Rain Storm” and “Test me, Test me” verses are, shall we say, “crackling with energy!!!” and Brent is fired up too, vocally ad libbing “goin down”.
Some hater reviewing another upload of this show disses the first set and this RFK 90 show in general and he fails to even mention the “Music Never Stopped” stating they abandon Deal after Jed. Huh? What? Trolls, what ya gonna do? This tells me he either didn’t listen to this gem, moreover he was never at this show because, you see imo this is the most powerful version of “The Music Never Stopped” ever played! From any era.
Anecdotal side note, I was positioned Phil side, left of stage, perhaps 20 to 30 feet away, when amidst this pouring down rainstorm, an orange beam of sunshine, splintered sunlight if you will, burst through the storm clouds illuminating  Mr. Garcia during both the bridge and mind bending outro guitar solo to this most stupendous closer. It was during this most stupendously intense part of this most epic version of the MNS, that my eyes became transfixed, my dilated pupils locking onto Jerry as he was musically locked and dialed in himself. It was as if I’d been struck with some kind of a magnetic tractor beam, drawing me ever closer, focusing my attention squarely onto Jerry, whose gray dome at this point  morphed into an enormous glowing undulating lion’s mane during this, hands down most intense Music Never Stopped outro guitar solo ever! Now this was particularly peculiar because Jerry happened to be sporting a short hair cut on this fine hot wet psychedelic summer day. Nevertheless, this lions mane, to my eyes at least, was indeed glowing and undulating, like Bruce Lee Roy’s glow… when he’s got to get to got to have that glow! Last Dragon anyone? So yeah, Phil’s thick bass, Jerry’s heavy heady playing, heavy rain, just a sick show!  Oh yeah, during the second set Foolish Heart jam into Dark Star, into swirling RFK Godzilla stadium shaking drum swirl, all the wet heads in front of the stage began stammering, speaking at 3/4 speed, blinded by inter dimensional strobe lights, eyes blinking, just slithering and stumbling through the mud in the infield, like dozens and dozens of Fear &Loathing lizard people. But alas, alls well that ends well I suppose, as in the end we did get by and we did survive, albeit with snap, crackle and pop accompanying us for our journey homeward and into the next day.
 In summation, there are shows I barely recall and there are *other one's I have no desire to revisit, but it’s this one here folks, 7/12/90, emblazoned into my consciousness, my very essence of being, as long as I’m lucky enough to exist on this shiny ball of blue, that sticks with me. Every smell, every sensation, every crowd noise, every note rushes back to me when I revisit this gem: 7-12-90.
There’s no other show that sounds quite like this one, and I am Grateful that I was lucky enough to attend.

my first show BUT still....

My older brother Mark took me to this one. I was 15 years old and he was 22 or 23. It was the summer before my sophomore year in high school. He was still in college but he had been to probably a hundred shows by then easy. This show basically blew my mind. Afterwards he said that I was super lucky to have gone to a show for my first one that was basically one of the best shows he had ever seen. And all of his friends who were people going to show his regularly agreed. So I knew there was something special going on. Also, there seem to be something special about RFK Stadium and this seemed to carry through until at least 1993 if not all the way through to the end arguably.
